The tenant of Bakal: The stoves are heating, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man came out through the door of the RPG Byty customer center of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He carried under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel," point out on his son's new contract the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed anyway," he explained, angry and half resigned.
The citizens' association of BytyOKD.cz apartments which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until 7 December, when a notice will be published to explain the method to be followed to claim.
But the man reacts to this by a gesture of the hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not match the market price.
For this reason Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska Street is one of the four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "2011 rent", is lit on the touch screen.
Only one pressure and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" that your number is already starting to light up on the large screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to find out about the rent, but the new rents don't seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," replied, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The deragulation and the old apartments of minors of Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of parliament and from the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported this in a fairly sustained way before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change me a board put...n in the toilet, relieves in introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised RPG in a special offer.
This is a rebate of half of the rent to be paid to other landlords who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the questions.
"Among the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent," says the employee at the counter.
And yet RPG posts individual interviews on rents when necessary, both on its website and in showcases.
If both parties do not agree on the rent, the decision will be made by an independent tribunal.
'It's not about threats, it's only about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally," says RPG on its website.
"Here no one will go to court" thinks one of RPG Byty's employees and the man in the street in front of the customer center is right.
"I have 13,000 retirement crowns and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court," he says.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore the people wait," she says.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the rent increase.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able with rents to invest in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hung from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs of the waiting room of Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments".
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," says the screen.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, it is an increase of a really low sum 19.66 Czech crowns per square metre," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money for the increase in rents (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices have included architects.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini nursery school with everything you need - color walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural-project company Arch. Design. whose workshops produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini nursery school of enterprise since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially of the age, to make children, and it was important for women architects and project managers to be able to return to work quickly.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, the nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this nursery school and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini nursery school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Human Resources Operational Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to funding (to the tune of 2.8 thousand Czech kroner), they were able to purchase equipment and appliances and after two years provide qualified personnel and start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the Arch. Design. company has the obligation after 3 years to run the mini nursery school from its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and Economy rating helped to apply for funding.
Children are cared for by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children all day long. Children can go to nursery school without any age limit, but they are more than three years old for the most part.
As it is a "mini nursery school" there can be only 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more that replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it takes on individual care and education, the programme of the mini nursery school is comparable to that of pre-school education.
Children do not just play there, but quality education is also provided - from the beginning to school preparation English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not be under the stress of being late to pick up children at a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is no surprise that a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer is being created.
Arch.Design.is thus registered among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house fascinates again after 100 years. Take a look in Gaudi's interiors.
The toit resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and balconies to open fish mouths.
Thus is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house was given the nickname "Bold House" by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see geometry, rhythm and thought order with precision.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the oeilleton and the slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number. 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual reconstruction and cheaper.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for a representation apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and Guell Park in which there are other Gaudi's works.
Locals dubbed the hot house just after its finish because of its organic forms "the Bone House".
Others, with regard to the specific window opening mechanism, have called it "the house that yawns".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of St.George the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of construction sculpture contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with typical vents and fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the construction directives of then and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finishing the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
Members of the city council, for example, were not pleased that the pillars of construction were encroaching on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's call Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent toit terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received besides new facades a non-traditional frame and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with the skylights.
The two-colour game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark that on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house which was listed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits as they found it to be a lucrative business and extended the scope of the visits to common areas and the attic including the toit terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discounts.
The sum is still above Gaudi's entry price into the other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the residents of the building and visit the house completely.
