At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public contest
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handcuffed the local entrepreneur and shopkeeper in Lubos real estate.
The latter had endeavoured to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the land proposed was obtained by a particular candidate.
This one was supposed to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"For the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in a public tender and competition," said Plzen prosecutor Antonie Zelena's newspaper Pravo, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is under way.
The police released this 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
To know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate with regard to so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, the spokesperson for the Fonds des Terrains Lubomira Cerna said that the police had actually arrested in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a client and in no way an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Act" and is put in place when several eligible candidates manifest themselves.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to resituations which must be paid before the value of the land is announced".
"According to the proposed rights a ranking of the purchasers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights", explained the spokesperson of the Fund.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and, as he himself is, also a beneficiary because having bought a large number of rights to restitution, he had offered the candidates to the field not to participate in the competition.
And he probably cashed in by withdrawing.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts largely above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
He appeared in the case of former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted in criminal proceedings for editing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been edited.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access artery to the Borske Pole industrial zone was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was obliged to accept because otherwise it risked endangering the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay a supplement of about a hundred crowns monthly for housing.
Households will have to pay a supplement from January onwards not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to draw from their wallets from January onwards up to a hundred crowns monthly more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to one tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 more crowns per year for households in flats than at present.
However, all suppliers have reduced electricity prices given the significant development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energy, including photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
So there are also about a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in central heating prices differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 more crowns per month, families in Libérec will pay more than 1,000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague an increase of 9 per cent for water and sanitation in case the city increases the infrastructure rents.
If rents do not change the Pragois will pay a surcharge of 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest compared to the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are increasing by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will rise significantly, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments rented from January onwards, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example the company CPI Byty which owns in Usti nad Labem almost 2500 apartments, has decided an increase up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new increase in rents will be brought before the courts by the company.
The regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300 thousand apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for re-offending are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to the admissions of children's departments in hospitals.
"Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk".
'The trend is really strong alcohol," says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, Head of the Children's Department of Horovice Hospital in Central Bohemia.
"When they manage to pick up a bottle of daddy's in the closet, it's sometimes about wisky but it's the fernet and vodka that prevail."
"The vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and so don't feel it," explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, is also right.
"In general, it's rum or fernet".
"It's now fashionable alcohol especially in elementary schools".
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," added Jurinova.
According to the Head of Department Pélikan, seeing drunk children between the ages of 13 and 14 in hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in paediatrics where ambulances brought school children from the wide, completely drunk surroundings.
"A young girl was hospitalized four times
"She started her career at twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with in addition a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party".
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem weird to the mother that her daughter was away for 48 hours," said the Director of the Department.
It is precisely the parents' disinterestedness or their extraordinary tolerance for the fact that their offspring drink which is the main cause of the development of children's alcoholism.
According to experts, however, there is no mention of dependence, in its strict sense, on children.
"Under the term alcoholic one hears a chronic addiction to alcohol of several years with all the phenomena which result from it but which one does not find in children".
"In those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is rather a socio-familial background that is significantly unfavourable," explained the Head of Department Pelikan.
According to spokesperson Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with a grâve intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Intoxicated children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, it exites three seasonal waves with which one can count: the day of witches, Saint Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Be they drink out of spite after bad results either on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holiday".
"Of course I lived on witch's day an admission of seven drunken children at once," stressed Pelikan.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in rehab under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffered the day after the "wood guule".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have an excellent evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them".
"They are only surprised where they are," adds Pelikan, knowing that from time to time this spoils the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care bed hospitalization can range up to tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time, I have applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they could spend the whole summer on seasonal work to pay back a single evening," added Pelikan.
However, in his view, health insurance companies in their declining management, which should recover the costs of care from parents, do not deal with cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defence exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that such aircraft have become the property of anyone other than the Czech Army.
However, they have been abroad in exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were up to now in service in the Czech Army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three devices are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical departure of Vodochody's aircraft is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for exchange have been taken from long-storage aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence".
"The L-159 T1 dual-seaters were traded in the state," said for Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not remain without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two-seaters.
The Army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second aircraft scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that whoever takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used for training pilots from NATO member countries".
"It is therefore the case of the one who takes into account to determine how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159 for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by Mirek Topomanek's government.
The Ministry of Defence did not tender and contacted EADS directly.
Defence management argued that the exchange would ensure a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and uses only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will probably have legal implications.
the European Commission has nevertheless filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence to the European Court of Justice because the planes should have been chosen in the framework of a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with longer indexes than ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under the age of 60," declared the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those with the longer index than the annular, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, and for men before age 60, the risk decreased to 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two mentioned fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps to develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for TKC that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
