Can civility bring cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invectiveness and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a forerunner of genuine bipartite cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the "Luck Duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the Committee on the Chairman's deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments by participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties stay miles away.
Yet the November election moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions and then fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, notably those on the agenda of the "Limp Duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, more optimism was expressed on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "Limp Duck", with the ratification of the "New START" Pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what is going on between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacle or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea which contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their opinion, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group; this suggests that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston is planning two phases in the fighting between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged to be in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there were then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort is needed on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
