The government of Belarus announced on Wednesday that it will abandon its stock of highly enriched uranium, an essential component for nuclear weapons; this decison is part of a surprise victory of President Obama's campaign to secure nuclear material worldwide
The agreement was disclosed in a joint communiqué issued after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met here with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the margins of a security summit.
The US government had tried for years to convince Belarus to abandon highly enriched uranium and seemed to have cleared the horizon last spring.
But US officials told the Washington Post that some classified operations have been carried out with Belarus over the past two months to eliminate 187 pounds of military-grade uranium from a Belarus research center.
This paved the way for an agreement on Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the matter of about 500 pounds, according to an official who referred to the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement seems to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit, convened by Obama, where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was beneficial to provide an invitation to the former Soviet Republic following the summit, in 2012.
"I'm really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit Nuclear Security Summit."
"This proves to me that this process is working," said Ken Luongo, President of the Global Security Partnership, a group promoting nuclear security.
Clinton called the agreement "a very significant, important step" made by Belarus.
Obama pledged in Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear material around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under George W. Bush's administration.
At the Obama Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko said that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have kept highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially military-grade uranium and low enriched uranium," said Mr Lukashenko.
"This is our product... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell it to anyone."
"We're just going to use it for research purposes, that's all."
Belarus moved closer to the United States a few months ago; however, by showing interest in reaching an agreement.
The first implementation to eliminate uranium from Belarus in October was particularly complicated as the equipment had been slightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded on a special train that traveled over 1,300 miles to a facility in Russia to be stored and disposed of, officials said.
The second operation was completed on Monday and was flown, according to officials.
The U.S. government spent $13 million in its efforts, largely to replace Belarus' research facilities with low enriched uranium; unsuitable for weapons.
"Detailed coordination and organization have been implemented to build confidence," leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, a head of the Energy Department specializing in Global Threat Reduction.
According to estimates of the James Martin Center for Non-Proliferation Studies, this year Belarus had at least 88 pounds of military-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilos of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus is seeking to eliminate its stocks by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to the harsh repression of human rights by Lukashenko.
But Wednesday's statement suggested a potential renewal.
"While welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus recognised that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remained essential to improving bilateral relations; and essential to the progress of the country and its citizens," she said.
