Sport and fraud of the law
The ruses similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion in principle by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match of November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink on the anti-sport character of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team already clearly won), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next barrage match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without boxes in the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned team coach José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved with two games.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case relates to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his hymn displays nobility and honor and who in past occasions sentenced his players to a fine for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour does not expressly prohibit by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether with these actions one commits a fraud by law; for, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to look at the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, i.e. there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that are referred to with the correct game is to prevent the infractory players' team from profiting in an unfair way from the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in hiding to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They were waiting and they willingly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders get from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the rival in a disadvantage situation and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because of course the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on those players.
Of course the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, as the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than at the first round.
So, climbing the ladders, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which is nevertheless part of the decision-making strategy that favours the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without foiling the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was passed on to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
