The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Service Centres for Visa Applicants prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Service Centres for Visa Applicants (CSA) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for aspirants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visa applications (this includes visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for visas for traders and investors.
Individuals wishing to renew their visas will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only report to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be made in the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
