The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the third quarter
The unemployment rate in France in the sense of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the seasonally adjusted data (SSCs) published on Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed in metropolitan France stands at 2,631 million.
Data for the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the working population in metropolitan France and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over one year, the unemployment rate has risen by 0.1 percentage points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, rising to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 point over three months, +0.5 point over one year) and 25% by including the DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed under the ILO.
Seniors, for their part, experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+0.2 percentage points over three months and one year), i.e. 482,000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only 25-49 year-olds enjoyed stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 percentage point over three months, +0.1 percentage point over one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
INSEE has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (including DOM) in October after 9.9% in September.
