Clotilde Reiss case: the Elysée exaggerated Syria's mediation
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher arrested in Iran for "spying", held the public in suspense in France, alerted diplomacy, and accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of the diplomats of the United States.
American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some of the undersides of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée explained its strategy to the Americans, going so far as to give them advice on the treatment of their own "hostages" crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young French woman had not been matched by the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and sought by the American justice system for trafficking in materials for the benefit of Iran's nuclear program.
Finally, they place under raw light the way the French presidency sought to manipulate the media to accredit the idea that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad had played a central role in the liberation of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, it was nothing of the sort.
A diplomatic telegram written on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to manage hostage cases".
The Elysée advisor for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, meet with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method to him.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own forcibly detained nationals to Iran.
"Make noise," they say, "get the words "fundamental human rights", "innocent", "immediate liberation" in the media.
It is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"Do it all the more as Iranians ask you not to do it".
Because, past attempts at discussions through discreet channels, "silence will not settle anything", the Iranians are "masters in delaying maneuvers".
Mr Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is "a familiar Iranian tactic: taking hostages for political blackmail".
He announced that the release of Clotilde Reiss prison (which will take place on 16 August, the day she takes refuge at the French embassy) "will require the payment of a large amount of money to Iranians" (230,000 euros of bail).
And he points out that the Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will worsen".
Iranians could "in the near future arrest another of some 1,800 French citizens living in Iran," he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss has been out of prison for 12 days, but remains stranded in Iran.
Information is being disseminated: Iran's Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is being requested by the United States for illegal trafficking of sensitive electronic material to Iran, is being released in Paris, by a judge's decision.
The American embassy, like many observers, wonders about this disturbing coincidence.
For Washington, which is tracking down Iran's clandestine networks for the acquisition of nuclear-related equipment, the expansion of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France accept a bargain?
The liberation of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a further interview with Kathleen Allegrone on 4 September, François Richier assured that this was not the case.
The Elysée, he said, was not only "completely taken by surprise by the judge's decision", but sought to oppose it.
"There have been lively exchanges between the French Presidency and the keeper of seals" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot reverse the decision", he observes.
Mr. Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the "close" supervision of French intelligence services.
The Elysée advisor dials a phone number, hangs up, and then informs the American diplomat that the Iranian "is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy".
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée does not spare its efforts, by means of press releases and "leaks" organized in the media, to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an "important" and "influent" role as a "mediator".
The Americans observe this activity not without irony, and note that manipulation is bearing fruit since several press articles echo the official French version.
A telegram dated 25 August 2009 evokes "the media 'blitz' of French officials".
