In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even the baguette and chewing gum were stuffed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to warm the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" is "probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Europe Ecology-Greens Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "face to the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
